Well, of course:

US regulators sued crypto brokerages Genesis Global Capital and Gemini Trus=
t Co. for breaking securities rules.=C2=A0
The Securities and Exchange Commission said on Thursday that the firms ille=
gally raised billions of dollars from hundreds of thousands of investors th=
rough the so-called Gemini Earn program. That product, which let customers =
loan out their assets in exchange for interest payments, amounted to the of=
fering of unregistered securities, the SEC said.=C2=A0
Gemini launched Earn in February of 2021, with the idea of offering users p=
assive returns on their coins in exchange for the right to lend the tokens =
out. By August of that year, the program, which offered rates that far exce=
eded those on traditional bank accounts, crossed $3 billion in assets.=C2=
=A0

We=C2=A0covered this in 2021, when Coinbase Global Inc.=E2=80=99s similar c=
rypto lending=C2=A0program was shut down by the SEC before it started.=C2=
=A0I wrote:

Is lending your Bitcoins a security?
Oh, sure, yes, absolutely.=C2=A0The rule=C2=A0in the U.S. is that an =E2=80=
=9Cinvestment contract,=E2=80=9D meaning =E2=80=9Cthe investment of money i=
n a common enterprise with a reasonable expectation of profits to be derive=
d from the efforts of others,=E2=80=9D is a security, and generally can=E2=
=80=99t be sold to the public without registering it with the Securities an=
d Exchange Commission, delivering a prospectus with audited financial state=
ments, etc. A Bitcoin lending program =E2=80=94 in which (1) a bunch of peo=
ple pool their Bitcoins, (2) some manager or smart contract lends those Bit=
coins to borrowers who pay interest, and (3) some or all of the interest is=
 paid back to the people in the pool =E2=80=94=C2=A0is pretty straightforwa=
rdly=C2=A0an investment contract and thus a security.

This is easy stuff. People in crypto don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0like=C2=A0it, but t=
hat=E2=80=99s because they are wrong. More specifically, they have an intui=
tion like =E2=80=9Cif a crypto platform pays you interest on your crypto de=
posits and uses them to make loans, that=C2=A0is like a bank account,=C2=A0=
and a bank account is not a security.=E2=80=9D
  [1]
=C2=A0But that=E2=80=99s because IT=E2=80=99S A BANK ACCOUNT. Like:

Securities regulator: Your Earn product is a security and needs to be regis=
tered with us.
Crypto platform operator: That=E2=80=99s ridiculous, Earn is just like a ba=
nk account, that=E2=80=99s not a security.
Banking regulator: Hi! I couldn=E2=80=99t help overhearing. Did you just sa=
y that YOU WOULD LIKE US TO REGULATE YOU AS A BANK?
Crypto platform operator: [screams, dives out window]

As I wrote in 2021:
Coinbase=C2=A0obviously=C2=A0does not want to be regulated as a bank; it do=
es not want to be subject to bank capital requirements (which require=C2=A0=
essentially 100% equity capital=C2=A0backing Bitcoin positions) or prudenti=
al regulation by bank regulators who like crypto about as much as the SEC d=
oes but have even more tools to crack down. You think the SEC is being anno=
ying about not issuing formal guidance! A bank examiner could just call you=
 up and say =E2=80=9Cwe don=E2=80=99t think owning Bitcoin is a good idea, =
get rid of it,=E2=80=9D and then where would Coinbase be?
So, right. Gemini has an Earn product=C2=A0where it gives its customers int=
erest on their crypto; it gets that interest by lending their crypto to Gen=
esis Global Capital LLC, a unit of Barry Silbert=E2=80=99s Digital Currency=
 Group. Genesis,=C2=A0in turn, lends the crypto to, you know,   Three Arrow=
s Capital,   Alameda Research, things of that nature. Oops! Last year Genes=
is lost a bunch of the money and eventually shut down withdrawals, includin=
g for Gemini Earn customers; Cameron Winklevoss has been sending Silbert so=
me nasty open letters about it. I don=E2=80=99t really disagree with the na=
sty letters, but they are kind of absurd coming from Winklevoss: Sure, it w=
as bad for Genesis to lose Gemini=E2=80=99s customers=E2=80=99 money, but i=
t was pretty much equally bad for Gemini to let them? Nobody made=C2=A0good=
=C2=A0decisions here.
The SEC seems to see it my way, and last week it sued Genesis and Gemini, t=
ogether, for this mess. Specifically  for doing unregistered securities off=
erings:

The Securities and Exchange Commission today charged Genesis Global Capital=
, LLC and Gemini Trust Company, LLC for the unregistered offer and sale of =
securities to retail investors through the Gemini Earn crypto asset lending=
 program. Through this unregistered offering, Genesis and Gemini raised bil=
lions of dollars=E2=80=99 worth of crypto assets from hundreds of thousands=
 of investors. Investigations into other securities law violations and into=
 other entities and persons relating to the alleged misconduct are ongoing.
According to the complaint, in December 2020, Genesis, part of a subsidiary=
 of Digital Currency Group, entered into an agreement with Gemini to offer =
Gemini customers, including retail investors in the United States, an oppor=
tunity to loan their crypto assets to Genesis in exchange for Genesis=E2=80=
=99 promise to pay interest. Beginning in February 2021, Genesis and Gemini=
 began offering the Gemini Earn program to retail investors, whereby Gemini=
 Earn investors tendered their crypto assets to Genesis, with Gemini acting=
 as the agent to facilitate the transaction. Gemini deducted an agent fee, =
sometimes as high as 4.29 percent, from the returns Genesis paid to Gemini =
Earn investors. As alleged in the complaint, Genesis then exercised its dis=
cretion in how to use investors=E2=80=99 crypto assets to generate revenue =
and pay interest to Gemini Earn investors.
The complaint further alleges that, in November 2022, Genesis announced tha=
t it would not allow its Gemini Earn investors to withdraw their crypto ass=
ets because Genesis lacked sufficient liquid assets to meet withdrawal requ=
ests following volatility in the crypto asset market. At the time, Genesis =
held approximately $900 million in investor assets from 340,000 Gemini Earn=
 investors. Gemini terminated the Gemini Earn program earlier this month. A=
s of today, the Gemini Earn retail investors have still not been able to wi=
thdraw their crypto assets.
The SEC=E2=80=99s complaint alleges that the Gemini Earn program constitute=
s an offer and sale of securities under applicable law and should have been=
 registered with the Commission.

Here is  the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint, which comes to a brisk 22 pages. The =
main argument that this is a security is on pages 13 to 19. Under the Secur=
ities Act of 1933, the  definition of =E2=80=9Csecurity=E2=80=9D includes a=
 bunch of different things, but the two that are relevant here are a =E2=80=
=9Cnote=E2=80=9D and an =E2=80=9Cinvestment contract.=E2=80=9D There are tw=
o Supreme Court cases =E2=80=94=C2=A0Reves v. Ernst & Young and SEC v. W.J.=
 Howey & Co.=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0that decided what makes an investment a =
=E2=80=9Cnote=E2=80=9D or an =E2=80=9Cinvestment contract=E2=80=9D under th=
is law. The SEC summarizes Reves:
A note is presumed to be a security unless it bears a strong resemblance to=
 instruments that are not securities, which courts determine by examining f=
our factors: (1) the motivation of the parties; (2) the plan of distributio=
n; (3) the expectations of the investing public; and (4) the availability o=
f an alternative regulatory regime that =E2=80=9Csignificantly reduces the =
risk of the instrument=E2=80=9D for investors other than the securities law=
s, =E2=80=9Cthereby rendering application of the Securities Acts unnecessar=
y.=E2=80=9D
Here, publicly marketing Gemini Earn as an investment to hundreds of thousa=
nds of retail investors probably makes it a security. The =E2=80=9Calternat=
ive regulatory regime=E2=80=9D stuff is basically the point that bank accou=
nts are not securities: If Gemini Earn were subject to banking regulation, =
then it might not be a security, but that is not the case. The SEC says:

Although Gemini is registered with [New York State Department of Financial =
Services]=C2=A0as a New York limited purpose trust company, NYSDFS did not =
have oversight over Genesis. Gemini publicly stated that Gemini Earn does n=
ot operate like a traditional bank account, is not protected by a governmen=
tal program, and is not backed by Gemini itself. In a February 2021 press r=
elease launching Gemini Earn, Gemini stated that =E2=80=9CGemini Earn is no=
t a depository account. . . . Loans are not insured by Gemini or any govern=
mental program or institution.=E2=80=9D Likewise, on its website, Gemini no=
ted that =E2=80=9CGemini Earn is structured similarly to non-deposit servic=
es offered by financial institutions and not insured by FDIC, SIPC, any oth=
er governmental program, or Gemini.=E2=80=9D
  [2]

Any capital reserve requirements applicable to Gemini did not apply to Gene=
sis or to the crypto assets tendered to Genesis through Gemini Earn.
  [3]


It=E2=80=99s not a bank account, which makes it probably a security.=C2=A0
Meanwhile the=C2=A0Howey=C2=A0test of what makes an =E2=80=9Cinvestment con=
tract=E2=80=9D a security is the one I quoted above; it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9C=
the investment of money in a common enterprise with a reasonable expectatio=
n of profits to be derived from the efforts of others.=E2=80=9D Gemini=E2=
=80=99s Earn customers invested money (their crypto) in a common enterprise=
 (Genesis=E2=80=99s lending business) with a reasonable (?) expectation of =
profits (their promised yield) that would be derived from the efforts of ot=
hers (Genesis=E2=80=99s lending decisions). The SEC says:

From its inception, Defendants have explicitly marketed the Gemini Earn pro=
gram as an investment opportunity which led investors to reasonably expect =
to profit from their efforts. As detailed above, through their websites and=
 social media channels, both Genesis and Gemini publicly touted the ability=
 for investors to earn yield or returns via Gemini Earn. Gemini repeatedly =
itself described Gemini Earn as an investment on its own website; repeatedl=
y touted that the Gemini Earn interest rates were =E2=80=9Camong the highes=
t rates on the market=E2=80=9D and that Gemini Earn investors could =E2=80=
=9Creceive more than 100x the national interest rate=E2=80=9D; and Gemini=
=E2=80=99s website illustrated how much interest Gemini Earn investors coul=
d potentially earn by investing their crypto assets for a period between on=
e and four years.
Genesis also described itself as the =E2=80=9Cpremier institutional digital=
 asset financial services firm,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cthe world=E2=80=99s l=
argest digital asset lender=E2=80=9D and that =E2=80=9C[h]olders of digital=
 currencies can earn yield on their assets by lending directly to Genesis, =
a regulated and trusted counterparty.=E2=80=9D Accordingly, Gemini Earn inv=
estors were led to expect that Defendants=E2=80=99 efforts to generate the =
investment returns =E2=80=93 i.e., the promised interest =E2=80=93 would re=
sult in profit for investors.

It is probably helpful to=C2=A0the SEC, in making this case, that Genesis a=
nd Gemini seem to have lost the money, or at least, uh, rendered it inacces=
sible. The SEC=E2=80=99s essential argument here is that Gemini Earn is an =
investment of money in a risky profit-seeking venture whose success depends=
 on the efforts of Cameron Winklevoss and Barry Silbert; Gemini=E2=80=99s a=
nd Genesis=E2=80=99s essential argument is =E2=80=9Cno it isn=E2=80=99t, sh=
hh, it=E2=80=99s just a nice 8% return on your money.=E2=80=9D The fact tha=
t the money is gone, or at least temporarily indisposed, strengthens the SE=
C=E2=80=99s position. Ex post, it was definitely risky.
Of course it would have been better if the SEC had shut down Gemini Earn =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0like it did Coinbase Lend =E2=80=94=C2=A0before it lost the =
money, but that is hardly a defense now.=C2=A0
The main=20
remedy for doing an unregistered securities offering is that you have to gi=
ve the money back: If you raise $900 million from investors for your produc=
t, and then the product loses money, you have to give them their money back=
 anyway. Well, that and you probably have to pay a fine to the SEC.
Elsewhere, Bloomberg News reports on  the Ripple case:

In the wake of the implosion of cryptocurrency exchange FTX, one urgent que=
stion keeps resurfacing: Who should regulate the industry?
An upcoming ruling in New York federal court could help determine the answe=
r, along with the fates of numerous crypto investors and companies. The cas=
e hinges on whether a prominent digital token should be treated as a securi=
ty, which would fall under the Securities & Exchange Commission=E2=80=99s j=
urisdiction.=C2=A0
The dispute dates back to 2020, when the SEC accused San Francisco-based Ri=
pple Labs Inc. of selling unregistered digital tokens without adequate disc=
losure.=C2=A0

The issues in Ripple are not quite the same as the issues in Gemini Earn, b=
ut they are related; the basic question is whether courts will read the =E2=
=80=9Cinvestment contract=E2=80=9D rules as broadly as the SEC does. I thin=
k they will, but if the SEC loses the Ripple case then what I wrote above w=
ill probably be wrong, or at least, like, too strongly stated. But as that =
Bloomberg story notes, the broad crypto collapse probably helps the SEC=E2=
=80=99s position:

The recent turmoil in crypto markets=C2=A0could taint the court=E2=80=99s v=
iew,=C2=A0said Joseph Hall, a partner at Davis Polk & Wardwell who worked a=
t the SEC from 2003 to 2005.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CYou just have to imagine that the judges will be influenced by the=
 investor losses they=E2=80=99ve seen,=E2=80=9D Hall said. =E2=80=9CAnd the=
 SEC will make clear to them that if you rule the other way, we will not ha=
ve the tools that we need to fight this kind of activity.=E2=80=9D

Right. Ripple=E2=80=99s XRP token has lost a lot of value in the last coupl=
e of years, though it=E2=80=99s actually up a bit from where it was when th=
e SEC sued;=C2=A0in any case Ripple does have the vague moral defense of =
=E2=80=9Cyou say we did an unregistered securities offering, but it=E2=80=
=99s not like we took a bunch of investor money and=C2=A0lost=C2=A0it.=E2=
=80=9D Lots of other crypto projects, including Gemini Earn, do not have th=
at defense.=C2=A0

