r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">of course</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">US regulators sued crypto brokerages Genesis G=
lobal Capital and Gemini Trust Co. for breaking securities rules.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission said on=
 Thursday that the firms illegally raised billions of dollars from hundreds=
 of thousands of investors through the so-called Gemini Earn program. That =
product, which let customers loan out their assets in exchange for interest=
 payments, amounted to the offering of unregistered securities, the SEC sai=
d.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Gemini launched Earn in February of 2021, with=
 the idea of offering users passive returns on their coins in exchange for =
the right to lend the tokens out. By August of that year, the program, whic=
h offered rates that far exceeded those on traditional bank accounts, cross=
ed $3 billion in assets.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We=C2=A0covered this in 2021, when Coinbase Gl=
obal Inc.=E2=80=99s similar crypto lending=C2=A0program was shut down by th=
e SEC before it started.=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/30277130.281516/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2F=
ydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDktMDgvbGVuZGluZy1iaXRjb2lucy1pcy10cmlja3k_Y21waWQ9QkJEMD=
ExNzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImd=
XRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTE3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB2c41b34e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">I wrote</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is lending your Bitcoins a security?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh, sure, yes, absolutely.=C2=A0<a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30277130.281516/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjEtMDgtMDkvbW9uZXktc3R1ZmYtdGh=
lLXNlYy1oYXMtc29tZS1jcnlwdG8tY29tcGxhaW50cz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTE3MjNfTU9ORVlTVF=
VGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAxM=
TcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd7526852" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">The rule</a>=C2=A0in the U.S. is that an =E2=
=80=9Cinvestment contract,=E2=80=9D meaning =E2=80=9Cthe investment of mone=
y in a common enterprise with a reasonable expectation of profits to be der=
ived from the efforts of others,=E2=80=9D is a security, and generally can=
=E2=80=99t be sold to the public without registering it with the Securities=
 and Exchange Commission, delivering a prospectus with audited financial st=
atements, etc. A Bitcoin lending program =E2=80=94 in which (1) a bunch of =
people pool their Bitcoins, (2) some manager or smart contract lends those =
Bitcoins to borrowers who pay interest, and (3) some or all of the interest=
 is paid back to the people in the pool =E2=80=94=C2=A0is pretty straightfo=
rwardly=C2=A0an investment contract and thus a security.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is easy stuff. People in crypto don=E2=80=
=99t=C2=A0<em>like=C2=A0</em>it, but that=E2=80=99s because they are wrong.=
 More specifically, they have an intuition like =E2=80=9Cif a crypto platfo=
rm pays you interest on your crypto deposits and uses them to make loans, t=
hat=C2=A0is like a bank account,=C2=A0and a bank account is not a security.=
=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-col=
or: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But that=E2=80=99s because IT=E2=80=99S A BANK ACCOUNT. Like:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Securities regulator:</strong> Your Ea=
rn product is a security and needs to be registered with us.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Crypto platform operator:</strong> Tha=
t=E2=80=99s ridiculous, Earn is just like a bank account, that=E2=80=99s no=
t a security.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Banking regulator:</strong> Hi! I coul=
dn=E2=80=99t help overhearing. Did you just say that YOU WOULD LIKE US TO R=
EGULATE YOU AS A BANK?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Crypto platform operator:</strong> [<e=
m>screams, dives out window</em>]</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As I wrote in 2021:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Coinbase=C2=A0<em>obviously=C2=A0<=
/em>does not want to be regulated as a bank; it does not want to be subject=
 to bank capital requirements (which require=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30277130.281516/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJ=
nLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMTAvbWF5YmUtZ2FtZXN0b3AtaXMtZ29vZC=
1ub3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDExNzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291c=
mNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTE3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe87fecf5" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">essenti=
ally 100% equity capital</a>=C2=A0backing Bitcoin positions) or prudential =
regulation by bank regulators who like crypto about as much as the SEC does=
 but have even more tools to crack down. You think the SEC is being annoyin=
g about not issuing formal guidance! A bank examiner could just call you up=
 and say =E2=80=9Cwe don=E2=80=99t think owning Bitcoin is a good idea, get=
 rid of it,=E2=80=9D and then where would Coinbase be?</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So, right. Gemini has an Earn product=C2=A0whe=
re it gives its customers interest on their crypto; it gets that interest b=
y lending their crypto to Genesis Global Capital LLC, a unit of Barry Silbe=
rt=E2=80=99s Digital Currency Group. Genesis,=C2=A0in turn, lends the crypt=
o to, you know, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30=
277130.281516/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwM=
jItMTItMDUvY3J5cHRvLWhhZC1hLWNyZWRpdC1idWJibGU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDExNzIzX01PTkVZ=
U1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjM=
wMTE3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe71ad6dc" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">  Three Arrows Capital</a>, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/30277130.281516/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9=
uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMTIvanBtb3JnYW4tc2F5cy1mcmFuay13YXMtZnJhdWQ_Y21waW=
Q9QkJEMDExNzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZ=
XR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTE3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cBb5384514" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  Alameda Research</a>, things of that nature=
. Oops! Last year Genesis lost a bunch of the money and eventually shut dow=
n withdrawals, including for Gemini Earn customers; Cameron Winklevoss has =
been sending Silbert some <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/30277130.281516/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGl=
jbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMTAvY3J5cHRvLWJhbmtzLW93ZS10aGVtc2VsdmVzLW1vbmV5P2NtcGlkPU=
JCRDAxMTcyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0d=
GVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDExNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB01a517bc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">nasty open letters</a> about it. I don=E2=80=99t =
really disagree with the nasty letters, but they are kind of absurd coming =
from Winklevoss: Sure, it was bad for Genesis to lose Gemini=E2=80=99s cust=
omers=E2=80=99 money, but it was pretty much equally bad for Gemini to let =
them? Nobody made=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>decisions here.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC seems to see it my way, and last week =
it sued Genesis and Gemini, together, for this mess. Specifically <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30277130.281516/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMy03/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cBf562a9b8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> for doing unregistered securities offerings</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission today c=
harged Genesis Global Capital, LLC and Gemini Trust Company, LLC for the un=
registered offer and sale of securities to retail investors through the Gem=
ini Earn crypto asset lending program. Through this unregistered offering, =
Genesis and Gemini raised billions of dollars=E2=80=99 worth of crypto asse=
ts from hundreds of thousands of investors. Investigations into other secur=
ities law violations and into other entities and persons relating to the al=
leged misconduct are ongoing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According to the complaint, in December 2020, =
Genesis, part of a subsidiary of Digital Currency Group, entered into an ag=
reement with Gemini to offer Gemini customers, including retail investors i=
n the United States, an opportunity to loan their crypto assets to Genesis =
in exchange for Genesis=E2=80=99 promise to pay interest. Beginning in Febr=
uary 2021, Genesis and Gemini began offering the Gemini Earn program to ret=
ail investors, whereby Gemini Earn investors tendered their crypto assets t=
o Genesis, with Gemini acting as the agent to facilitate the transaction. G=
emini deducted an agent fee, sometimes as high as 4.29 percent, from the re=
turns Genesis paid to Gemini Earn investors. As alleged in the complaint, G=
enesis then exercised its discretion in how to use investors=E2=80=99 crypt=
o assets to generate revenue and pay interest to Gemini Earn investors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The complaint further alleges that, in Novembe=
r 2022, Genesis announced that it would not allow its Gemini Earn investors=
 to withdraw their crypto assets because Genesis lacked sufficient liquid a=
ssets to meet withdrawal requests following volatility in the crypto asset =
market. At the time, Genesis held approximately $900 million in investor as=
sets from 340,000 Gemini Earn investors. Gemini terminated the Gemini Earn =
program earlier this month. As of today, the Gemini Earn retail investors h=
ave still not been able to withdraw their crypto assets.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC=E2=80=99s complaint alleges that the G=
emini Earn program constitutes an offer and sale of securities under applic=
able law and should have been registered with the Commission.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/30277130.281516/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9u=
L2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyMy9jb21wLXByMjAyMy03LnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0ca=
c92e3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;"> the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint</a>, which comes to a brisk 22 =
pages. The main argument that this is a security is on pages 13 to 19. Unde=
r the Securities Act of 1933, the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/30277130.281516/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9=
uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDktMDgvbGVuZGluZy1iaXRjb2lucy1pcy10cmlja3k_Y21waWQ9Qk=
JEMDExNzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0Z=
XImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTE3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cC2c41b34e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> definition of =E2=80=9Csecurity=E2=80=9D</a> inclu=
des a bunch of different things, but the two that are relevant here are a =
=E2=80=9Cnote=E2=80=9D and an =E2=80=9Cinvestment contract.=E2=80=9D There =
are two Supreme Court cases =E2=80=94=C2=A0<em>Reves v. Ernst &amp; Young</=
em> and <em>SEC v. W.J. Howey &amp; Co.</em>=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0that decid=
ed what makes an investment a =E2=80=9Cnote=E2=80=9D or an =E2=80=9Cinvestm=
ent contract=E2=80=9D under this law. The SEC summarizes <em>Reves</em>:</p=
>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A note is presumed to be a securit=
y unless it bears a strong resemblance to instruments that are not securiti=
es, which courts determine by examining four factors: (1) the motivation of=
 the parties; (2) the plan of distribution; (3) the expectations of the inv=
esting public; and (4) the availability of an alternative regulatory regime=
 that =E2=80=9Csignificantly reduces the risk of the instrument=E2=80=9D fo=
r investors other than the securities laws, =E2=80=9Cthereby rendering appl=
ication of the Securities Acts unnecessary.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here, publicly marketing Gemini Earn as an inv=
estment to hundreds of thousands of retail investors probably makes it a se=
curity. The =E2=80=9Calternative regulatory regime=E2=80=9D stuff is basica=
lly the point that bank accounts are not securities: If Gemini Earn were su=
bject to banking regulation, then it might not be a security, but that is n=
ot the case. The SEC says:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Although Gemini is registered with [New York S=
tate Department of Financial Services]=C2=A0as a New York limited purpose t=
rust company, NYSDFS did not have oversight over Genesis. Gemini publicly s=
tated that Gemini Earn does not operate like a traditional bank account, is=
 not protected by a governmental program, and is not backed by Gemini itsel=
f. In a February 2021 press release launching Gemini Earn, Gemini stated th=
at =E2=80=9CGemini Earn is not a depository account. . . . Loans are not in=
sured by Gemini or any governmental program or institution.=E2=80=9D Likewi=
se, on its website, Gemini noted that =E2=80=9CGemini Earn is structured si=
milarly to non-deposit services offered by financial institutions and not i=
nsured by FDIC, SIPC, any other governmental program, or Gemini.=E2=80=9D<a=
 class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpa=
rent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Any capital reserve requirements applicable to=
 Gemini did not apply to Genesis or to the crypto assets tendered to Genesi=
s through Gemini Earn.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; b=
ackground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s not a bank account, which makes i=
t probably a security.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile the=C2=A0<em>Howey=C2=A0</em>test of=
 what makes an =E2=80=9Cinvestment contract=E2=80=9D a security is the one =
I quoted above; it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cthe investment of money in a common e=
nterprise with a reasonable expectation of profits to be derived from the e=
fforts of others.=E2=80=9D Gemini=E2=80=99s Earn customers invested money (=
their crypto) in a common enterprise (Genesis=E2=80=99s lending business) w=
ith a reasonable (?) expectation of profits (their promised yield) that wou=
ld be derived from the efforts of others (Genesis=E2=80=99s lending decisio=
ns). The SEC says:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From its inception, Defendants have explicitly=
 marketed the Gemini Earn program as an investment opportunity which led in=
vestors to reasonably expect to profit from their efforts. As detailed abov=
e, through their websites and social media channels, both Genesis and Gemin=
i publicly touted the ability for investors to earn yield or returns via Ge=
mini Earn. Gemini repeatedly itself described Gemini Earn as an investment =
on its own website; repeatedly touted that the Gemini Earn interest rates w=
ere =E2=80=9Camong the highest rates on the market=E2=80=9D and that Gemini=
 Earn investors could =E2=80=9Creceive more than 100x the national interest=
 rate=E2=80=9D; and Gemini=E2=80=99s website illustrated how much interest =
Gemini Earn investors could potentially earn by investing their crypto asse=
ts for a period between one and four years.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Genesis also described itself as the =E2=80=9C=
premier institutional digital asset financial services firm,=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9Cthe world=E2=80=99s largest digital asset lender=E2=80=9D and that=
 =E2=80=9C[h]olders of digital currencies can earn yield on their assets by=
 lending directly to Genesis, a regulated and trusted counterparty.=E2=80=
=9D Accordingly, Gemini Earn investors were led to expect that Defendants=
=E2=80=99 efforts to generate the investment returns =E2=80=93 i.e., the pr=
omised interest =E2=80=93 would result in profit for investors.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is probably helpful to=C2=A0the SEC, in mak=
ing this case, that Genesis and Gemini seem to have lost the money, or at l=
east, uh, rendered it inaccessible. The SEC=E2=80=99s essential argument he=
re is that Gemini Earn is an investment of money in a risky profit-seeking =
venture whose success depends on the efforts of Cameron Winklevoss and Barr=
y Silbert; Gemini=E2=80=99s and Genesis=E2=80=99s essential argument is =E2=
=80=9Cno it isn=E2=80=99t, shhh, it=E2=80=99s just a nice 8% return on your=
 money.=E2=80=9D The fact that the money is gone, or at least temporarily i=
ndisposed, strengthens the SEC=E2=80=99s position. Ex post, it was definite=
ly risky.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course it would have been better if the SEC=
 had shut down Gemini Earn =E2=80=94=C2=A0like it did Coinbase Lend =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0<em>before </em>it lost the money, but that is hardly a defense no=
w.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The main <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/30277130.281516/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGl=
uaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTAtMDQvYmFyY2xheXMtbG9zdC10cmFjay1vZi1pdHMtbm90ZX=
M_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDExNzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlP=
W5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTE3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB5915e2c0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">
remedy for doing an unregistered securities offering</a> is that you have t=
o give the money back: If you raise $900 million from investors for your pr=
oduct, and then the product loses money, you have to give them their money =
back anyway. Well, that and you probably have to pay a fine to the SEC.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elsewhere, Bloomberg News reports on <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30277130.281516/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMTcvZnR4LWNvbGxhcHNl=
LXB1dHMtZm9jdXMtb24tcmlwcGxlLWNhc2UtZm9yLXdoby1zaG91bGQtcmVndWxhdGUtY3J5cHR=
vP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMTcyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT=
1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDExNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cBc3b14460" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the Ripple case</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the wake of the implosion of cryptocurrency=
 exchange FTX, one urgent question keeps resurfacing: Who should regulate t=
he industry?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An upcoming ruling in New York federal court c=
ould help determine the answer, along with the fates of numerous crypto inv=
estors and companies. The case hinges on whether a prominent digital token =
should be treated as a security, which would fall under the Securities &amp=
; Exchange Commission=E2=80=99s jurisdiction.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The dispute dates back to 2020, when the SEC a=
ccused San Francisco-based Ripple Labs Inc. of selling unregistered digital=
 tokens without adequate disclosure.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The issues in Ripple are not quite the same as=
 the issues in Gemini Earn, but they are related; the basic question is whe=
ther courts will read the =E2=80=9Cinvestment contract=E2=80=9D rules as br=
oadly as the SEC does. I think they will, but if the SEC loses the Ripple c=
ase then what I wrote above will probably be wrong, or at least, like, too =
strongly stated. But as that Bloomberg story notes, the broad crypto collap=
se probably helps the SEC=E2=80=99s position:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The recent turmoil in crypto markets=C2=A0coul=
d taint the court=E2=80=99s view,=C2=A0said Joseph Hall, a partner at Davis=
 Polk &amp; Wardwell who worked at the SEC from 2003 to 2005.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CYou just have to imagine that the jud=
ges will be influenced by the investor losses they=E2=80=99ve seen,=E2=80=
=9D Hall said. =E2=80=9CAnd the SEC will make clear to them that if you rul=
e the other way, we will not have the tools that we need to fight this kind=
 of activity.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Right. Ripple=E2=80=99s XRP token has lost a l=
ot of value in the last couple of years, though it=E2=80=99s actually up a =
bit from where it was <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/30277130.281516/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjA=
yMC0zMzg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8c73a2f9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">when the SEC sued</a>;=
=C2=A0in any case Ripple does have the vague moral defense of =E2=80=9Cyou =
say we did an unregistered securities offering, but it=E2=80=99s not like w=
e took a bunch of investor money and=C2=A0<em>lost=C2=A0</em>it.=E2=80=9D L=
ots of other crypto projects, including Gemini Earn, do not have that defen=
se.=C2=A0</p>
